This lab environment is built using three virtual machines, each representing a different role within a typical enterprise security architecture. The goal is to simulate a real-world attack scenario and observe how security monitoring systems detect malicious activity.

Attacker Machine – Kali Linux

The attacker machine represents an external threat actor attempting to gain unauthorized access to the target system. This virtual machine runs Kali Linux, which is commonly used for penetration testing and security research.

In this lab, Kali Linux is used to perform several credential-based attacks against the victim machine. These attacks simulate common real-world techniques used by attackers to compromise systems.

Primary responsibilities of the attacker machine include:

Launching RDP brute force attacks against the Windows host

Performing SMB authentication brute force attempts

Conducting password spraying attacks against multiple user accounts

Generating authentication traffic that will later be analyzed in the SIEM

The attacker machine communicates directly with the victim system within the isolated lab network.

Victim Machine – Windows 11

The victim machine represents a typical enterprise workstation targeted by attackers. This system runs Windows 11 and hosts the services that will be attacked during the simulation.

To enable security monitoring, the victim machine is configured with several logging mechanisms.

Key components configured on the Windows system include:

Windows Security Event Logging to capture authentication events

Sysmon to record process creation and network activity

Splunk Universal Forwarder to send logs to the SIEM server

During the attack simulations, this machine generates various security events such as:

Failed login attempts

Successful authentications

Account lockouts

Process activity following login attempts

These logs provide the primary evidence used for detection and investigation.

SIEM Machine – Ubuntu Server (Splunk)

The SIEM machine acts as the central monitoring and analysis platform for the lab environment. This system runs Splunk Enterprise on an Ubuntu Server.

Its primary function is to collect, index, and analyze logs generated by the victim machine.

The SIEM system enables security analysts to:

Monitor authentication activity in real time

Detect brute force attack patterns

Correlate security events across multiple log sources

Identify Indicators of Compromise (IOCs)

Build dashboards and alerts for suspicious behavior

Logs from the Windows machine are forwarded to the SIEM using the Splunk Universal Forwarder, allowing analysts to investigate attack activity using Splunk search queries and dashboards.

Lab Communication Flow

The interaction between the machines follows a simple structure:

The Kali attacker machine initiates credential attacks.

The Windows victim machine processes authentication attempts and records security events.

These logs are forwarded to the Splunk SIEM server, where they are analyzed and visualized.

This architecture enables the lab to simulate a complete attack–detection workflow, similar to what is used in real Security Operations Centers (SOCs).
